<div class="panel panel-default">
    <div class="panel-body">
        <h3>Types of Surveys</h3>
        <br />
        All surveys must be aligned - collated against - an Activity. Within that requirement, there are a number of optional settings to control the <em>reach</em> of the survey when results are entered. <br />The screen shot below is from Setup: Surveys.
        <div class="text-center">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/CC Survey optional fields.png" title="This screen-shot is from Setup: Surveys - where surveys are defined." />
        </div>
        <dl>
            <dt>
                Active
            </dt>
            <dd>
                A tick box. Tick it if you want the survey to be available for data entry. Untick it to hide it from data entry (this does not loose any results)<br />      <br />
            </dd>
            <dt>
                Survey Name
            </dt>
            <dd>
                A free-form text name for the survey. Anything you like can go in here but it is best to describe what the survey is about. For example "Survey" is pretty meaningless but "End of Activity satisfaction survey" is a bit more meaningful.
                <br />      <br />
            </dd>
            <dt>
                Activity
            </dt>
            <dd>
                The Activity to which the survey is to apply.<br />   <br />
            </dd>
            <dt>
                All Clients
            </dt>
            <dd>
                A tick box. Normally, surveys only apply to clients who are enrolled into the associated Activity. Thus, you must normally enroll a client in an Activity if they are to have results processed. However, by ticking this box, <strong>all registered clients - everyone! -</strong> may have results entered.
                <br />
                This setting is often used for Annual Satisfaction Surveys where all clients may respond.<br />      <br />
            </dd>
            <dt>Allow Anonymous responses</dt>
            <dd>
                A tick box. Survey results are normally solicited, and entered against, registered clients. However, by ticking this box, the respondant need not be registered. (All responses are collated against a reserved 'client' called <em>Anonymous Persons</em>)

                <br />  <br />
            </dd>
            <dt>
                Number of Text Questions
            </dt>
            <dd>
                <img src="~/Content/Images/CC Survey entering - textural.png" title="This screen-shot is from Work With: Surveys - where surveys are entered." width="200" align="right" />
                How many free-format text questions do you wish to pose to your Clients? Any number from zero upwards. All textural response questions
                are labelled alphabetically such that the first response is entered against label A, the second B etc. This sequence continues beyond 'Z' to 'AA' etc.
                <br />
                <br />
            </dd>
            <dt>
                Number of Numeric Questions
            </dt>
            <dd>
                <img src="~/Content/Images/CC Survey entering - numeric.png" title="This screen-shot is from Work With: Surveys - where surveys are entered." width="200" align="right" />
                How many numeric - <em>scaled-response</em> -  questions do you wish to pose to your Clients? Any number from zero upwards. All numeric response questions
                are labelled numerically such that the first response is entered against label A, the second 2 etc.
            </dd>
        </dl>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="panel panel-default">
    <div class="panel-body">
        <h3>Types of Survey responses</h3>
        <p>
            Surveys requires either numerical, or textural, or both types of, responses to a series of questions.
            <dl>
                <dt>
                    Numerical
                </dt>
                <dd>
                    Are always <strong>graded</strong> with response values being from 1 - 7. These are interpreted thus:
                    <ol>
                        <li>Strongly disagree</li>
                        <li>Disagree</li>
                        <li>Tend to disagree</li>
                        <li>Neither agree nor disagree</li>
                        <li>Tend to agree</li>
                        <li>Agree</li>
                        <li>Strongly agree</li>
                    </ol>
                </dd>
                <dt>
                    Textural
                </dt>
                <dd>
                    Free-form text values. There are no restrictions what may be entered in these fields with the exception that the maximum character length is 255 characters.
                </dd>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </div>
