            <strong>Quick Start Tip!</strong> This is what you need to do to do the whole surveying thing...
        </div>
        <h3 id="paper-survey">Making your own Survey</h3>
        To Community Counts, you simply define the <strong>number</strong> of numerical/textural responses that you wish to collate. It is up to you to produce the <em>paper-based form</em> that may present your survey data-collection; Community Counts does not produce the questionnaires; but it does provide a structured way of entering these responses and then analysing them.
        <br />
        Here are the necessary steps to designing, producing and entering a Survey:
        <ol>
            <li>
                Decide on the Survey <em>design</em> that you need:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        Which Activity does it relate to?
                    </li>
                    <li>How many Questions?</li>
                    <li>(See 'Setup : Surveys' above)</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                Make your own paper-based survey:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        You can place your questions in <strong>any order you wish</strong> - say with a text question first and 2 numeric questions next and a final text question.
                        <ul>
                            <li>Just remember that all text questions are labelled <strong>alphabetically</strong> and all numeric questions are labelled <strong>numerically</strong>.</li>
                            <li>All your numeric questions must have responses of 1 - 7 available.</li>
                            <li>Ensure that you include the <strong>Unique Survey ID</strong> on the form for identification</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                Send out your questionnaires (Surveys). Get your responses
            </li>
            <li>Enter the results by using Work with: Surveys and entering them against the right <strong> Unique Survey ID</strong></li>
        </ol>
        <a href="https://www.surveymonkey.com/mp/writing-survey-questions/" target="_blank">This is a useful article of writing Surveys in general.</a>
    </div>
